    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 13.46,
      "end": 17.24,
      "text": "Recording by Marion Brown, Toronto, Canada.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 18.58,
      "end": 22.78,
      "text": "ASOP's Fables, the Town Mouse and the Country Mouse.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 23.8,
      "end": 24.72,
      "text": "Chapter 16",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 26.92,
      "end": 35.82,
      "text": "A Town Mouse and a Country Mouse were acquaintances, and the Country Mouse one day invited his friend to come and see him at his home in the fields.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 36.46,
      "end": 44.44,
      "text": "The Town Mouse came and they sat down to a dinner of barley corns and roots, the latter of which had a distinctly earthy flavor.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 45.28,
      "end": 53.9,
      "text": "The fair was not much to the taste of the guest, and presently he broke out with, my poor dear friend, you live here no better than the ants.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-008",
      "start": 53.9,
      "end": 64.86,
      "text": "Now you should just see how I fare. My larder is a regular horn of plenty. You must come and stay with me, and I promise you, you shall live on the fad of the land.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-009",
      "start": 65.72,
      "end": 75.58,
      "text": "So when he returned to town, he took the Country Mouse with him, and showed him into a larder containing flour and oatmeal and figs and honey and dates.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-010",
      "start": 75.58,
      "end": 82.64,
      "text": "The Country Mouse had never seen anything like it, and sat down to enjoy the luxuries his friend provided.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-011",
      "start": 83.64,
      "end": 88.42,
      "text": "But before they had well begun, the door of the larder opened and someone came in.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-012",
      "start": 88.92,
      "end": 94.6,
      "text": "The two mice scampered off and hid themselves in a narrow and exceedingly uncomfortable hole.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-013",
      "start": 95.3,
      "end": 101.96,
      "text": "Presently, when all was quiet, they ventured out again, but someone else came in, and off they scuttled again.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-014",
      "start": 102.96,
      "end": 112.34,
      "text": "This was too much for the visitor. Goodbye, said he, I'm off. You live in the lap of luxury, I can see, but you are surrounded by dangers.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-015",
      "start": 113.12,
      "end": 121.74,
      "text": "Whereas at home I can enjoy my simple dinner of roots and corn in peace. End of the town mouse and the Country Mouse.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
